An apology can be given as simply as "I'm sorry", and if it's accepted then sure, the end.

You might enjoy the book, The Loom of Language by Frederick Bodmer. He has a bunch of tips for picking up languages, and he focuses a lot on learning vocabulary and then stacking with similar languages at once.

Curiously the book is weird because it was written in the 1940s by an ESL Swiss guy. He calls English "Anglo-American" almost every time. He devotes 1 page to Russian and says it's impossible. He also wastes a chapter on invented languages like Esperanto.

The Esperanto thing is almost reasonable, but unworkable in reality. The idea was historically that you had your local language and your trade language. Whatever the village dialect was you would do important business in Latin, etc.

>Isn't the pronunciation of Arabic pretty difficult too?
It's pretty simple. There are just letters that we don't have in English. No P sound, there are kh and gh sounds.
>I'm guessing you're learning Standard Arabic?
Yes. I may visit some of the dialects later.
>Would you say there's much mutual intelligibility between the different varieties for a non native speaker?
My Arabic is Modern Standard Arabic and charitably the level of a 5 year old, so I'm not an expert. I have often understood Arabic spoken by native speakers. Dialects change the pronunciation of some letters so the "jeem" can be pronounced jeem, zheem, or geem in Egypt. Dialects also have some other vocabulary here and there. So I knew some Palestinian slang that an Iraqi didn't know.

Overall though I would say the best analog to Arabic dialects is if you imagined everyone in English studying BBC English at school and then going home to speak Hillybilly or Jamaican.

I don't know how you did the weight loss, but there are wrong ways to do it that fuck with you psychologically like weird restrictions on what you can eat and other nonsense.

There are two good ways to lose weight:
1) Fasting, short and intense and the mind stuff makes you reevaluate your thoughts on food (in a good way). Reveals any hang ups you have like snacking as a habit of boredom, snacking as a habit of stress, and other such stuff.
2) Keeping input relatively the same, maybe minor decrease like cutting out beer / soda, but increasing your output i.e. exercise. This really isn't tenable long term without a dedication to change your lifestyle. But it increases muscle / general fitness and is good.
Generally you want to do the first to get the bulk off, then the second to fine tune. Doing just the second, or some bastardization of the second, will fuck with you.
You can lose like 10 lbs a month if you do it right.
